Teaching teenagers politely is all about balancing respect with clear boundaries ‚Äî treating them as young adults, but guiding them firmly when needed.
Here are practical tips to make your lessons smooth, respectful, and effective:

1. Respect Them First

Use their names and greet them warmly.

Avoid talking down to them; speak as you would to a capable person learning something new.

Listen when they share opinions or ask questions ‚Äî even if the answer seems obvious.

2. Set Clear Expectations Early

Explain the class rules politely: ‚ÄúIn our class, we‚Ä¶‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúYou must‚Ä¶‚Äù.

Share the reason behind each rule ‚Äî teenagers respond better when they understand why.

3. Use ‚ÄúInviting‚Äù Language

Instead of commands, try:

‚ÄúCould you please‚Ä¶‚Äù

‚ÄúLet‚Äôs try this together.‚Äù

‚ÄúWhen you finish, we‚Äôll move on to‚Ä¶‚Äù

4. Correct Without Embarrassing

Give feedback privately when possible.

If correcting in front of others, soften it:

‚ùå ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs wrong.‚Äù

‚úÖ ‚ÄúAlmost! Let‚Äôs check this part again.‚Äù

5. Acknowledge Their Effort

Praise specific actions, not just the person:

‚ÄúI like how you explained your answer.‚Äù

‚ÄúYou really improved your pronunciation today.‚Äù

6. Encourage Participation Without Pressure

Give choices: ‚ÄúWould you like to read or answer?‚Äù

Use group activities so shy students feel safer contributing.

7. Model the Politeness You Expect

Always say ‚Äúplease,‚Äù ‚Äúthank you,‚Äù and ‚Äúexcuse me.‚Äù

Teenagers pick up tone and habits quickly ‚Äî if you‚Äôre polite, they‚Äôll mirror it.

The steak accordion (I did something bad)

Maximizing the crust on a steak is always a priority. The most effective method I‚Äôve found is to dry brine. Salt the steak several hours or ideally a day before cooking and place on a rack in the fridge - the salt will fully absorb leaving the exterior completely dry. With less moisture on the surface of the steak, the crust becomes stronger and more flavorful. 

Another way to maximize the crust is to increase the surface area. It‚Äôs the same reason why I strongly prefer regular French fries to thick potato wedges. Fries have more surface area per volume, leading to more crunch and seasoning per bite. 

This is what I was going for in this video. The surface area of the steak exposed to the grill is significantly higher, which means more seasoning and crust per bite. There is however a major drawback. 

The accordion shape leads to a steak that has become ‚Äúthinner‚Äù and thus cooks faster. This means less time on the grill. So despite the greater surface area, it has less time for the crust to develop. I found that dry brining and an extremely hot grill will help. Whether you consider it to be practical or not, it‚Äôs definitely a fun process to try!

2025-08-16.description:
Was bayoneting corpses illegal in ww2?

Imagine your whole squad is dead, you‚Äôre the last alive and the enemy is advancing. You have two options, surrender and become a prisoner of war or pretend to be dead.

You go with the latter option, grabbing the body of your friend and trying to hide under it, pretending you're dead as well. 

But to your horror, the enemy starts attacking the bodies around you, you pray they don‚Äôt do this to you but with half an eye open you see a bayonet and bam, you‚Äôre gone too. 

So did that soldier just commit a war crime?

Well Under international law, mutilating bodies is a war crime. The dead are legally protected and a soldier mustn't further unnecessarily harm them after they are clearly deceased. 

But, there's a catch. During WW1 and 2, especially in the Pacific wars. Some soldiers would pretend to be dead, only to spring up seconds later to shoot you from behind or pull a grenade, ending themselves and enemy soldiers with them. 

So to protect against this, If a soldier has reason to believe that the enemy may only be pretending to be dead then attacking corpses could be argued to be necessary as long as reasonable force is used

So in general no, especially as any soldier pretending to be dead could surrender instead.

Even though the Marine Corps is known as the toughest branch in the U.S. military‚Äîdisciplined, aggressive, combat-ready. They eat crayons like toddlers. They stuck with the original.

Most people doesn't know the reason behind this but, Marines have always been the target of jokes‚Äîmocked as barbaric, blunt, or not the brightest. And around 2010, a meme started spreading online: ‚ÄúMarines are so dumb, they eat crayons.‚Äù

But instead of getting defensive, the Corps did something no one expected not even those who mocks them. They leaned into it and made it part of the culture. They started eating crayons for real. What began as a roast turned into an inside joke and an unofficial tradition.
